  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Chace brought news of Henry Egbert Benson&apos;s poor health. There was a disagreement with the doctors&apos; diagnosis. Dr. Harrington escorted Henry E. Benson to Providence. Garrison is resigned to God&apos;s will regarding Henry E. Benson. Garrison writes: &quot;But, oh! the thought of losing our dear Henry, the bloom and prime of youth---one so amiable, so benevolent, so disinterested, so earnestly disposed, like his Saviour, to do good, so anxious to see this ruined world restored to its original perfectibility---a friend, a brother, yea, &apos;a brother beloved&apos;---how it moves the deep fountains of the soul! how it lacerates the heart!&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
